 world where human rights are most at risk. Emilie Hafner-Burton argues that more progress is possible if human rights promoters work strategically with the group of states that have dedicated resources to human rights protection. These human rights "stewards" can focus their resources on places where the tangible benefits to human rights are greatest. Success will require setting priorities as well as engaging local stakeholders such as nongovernmental organizations and national human rights institutions. To date, promoters of international human rights law have relied too heavily on setting universal goals and procedures and not enough on assessing what actually works and setting priorities. Hafner-Burton illustrates how, with a different strategy, human rights stewards can make international law more effective and also safeguard human rights for more of the world population.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aHuman rights. 7aLAW / International.2bisacsh  aHuman Rights Council.  aInternational Bill of Human Rights.  aUN Office of the High Commissioner for Human Rights.  aUnited Nations.  aabusive behavior.  acivil rights.  acomplaints mechanisms.  aconflict.  aconstitutions.  acredibility.  acrime.  acriminal law.  acultural rights.  adehumanization.  adeterrence.  adiplomacy.  adomestic politics.  aforeign policy.  ahuman behavior.  ahuman rights abuses.  ahuman rights commissions.  ahuman rights promotion.  ahuman rights protection.  ahuman rights violations.  ahuman rights.  ailliberalism.  ainsider politics.  aintelligence.  ainternational human rights law.  ainternational human rights.  ainternational law.  ainternational legal reform.  alegal customs.  alegal system.  alegitimacy.  aleverage.  alocalization.  amilitary intervention.  a